text.tspan: Coding regions in the genome are symbolized by arrows
These are regions that are transcribed into RNA, which gets translated into proteins
In less comples organisms, most of the genome is coding, for more comples it is less
In humans, coding regions are estimated to take up only 2% of the genome
Noncoding regions are shows on the genome as the space
Some noncoding DNA is transcribed into functional RNA
Pseudogenes are also present in noncoding DNA, these are
genes that are likely passed from ancestors but aren't used
Introns are portions of genes that are cut out when being made
Noncoding regions vary greatly across organisms, more so than
